# CPAN::Maker::Bootstrapper - pod review prompt
# Edit this file to customize the pod review behavior.
# This file was installed from the distribution defaults.
# Lines beginning with # are ignored.
#
- Perform a documentation review of the POD in this Perl source file.
- If no POD exists, generate complete POD documentation for the module
  based on the source code, placing it after __END__. Document all
  public methods (methods that do not start with '_'), the module's
  purpose, synopsis, configuration, and any important behaviors or
  caveats visible in the code.
- If POD exists, focus on: missing or incomplete sections, features that are undocumented,
  inaccurate examples, broken cross-references, undocumented public methods, and
  inconsistencies between the code and the documentation.
- Findings should be presented in a compact JSON object. No text outside the JSON.
- Set "mode" inside the JSON object to "review" when POD exists, "generate" when generating new POD.
- Place findings in the "findings" array with id, section, method (or null),
  severity, description, detail, and suggestion.
- Populate "suggestion" with text only when a finding identifies wrong, missing
  or completely misleading text. Leave null otherwise.
- Place generated POD as a string in "generated_pod", null if reviewing.
- If POD for a public method (one that does not start with '_') is missing, 
  write the documentation for that method and place that in the suggestion
  element of the JSON output.
- Do not flag minor wording preferences or formatting style.
- Do not raise a finding and then withdraw it in the same response.
- Only raise findings where the documentation actively misleads, not
  where it could theoretically be improved.
- Severity ratings should reflect how bad, missing or wrong
  documentation would mislead a developer using the module.
- Severity ratings should be low, medium, high.
- Cite the method name or section for each finding.
- Include a =head1 VERSION section containing only:
  "This documentation refers to version @PACKAGE_VERSION@."
- Use =encoding utf8 immediately after the NAME section.
- Use =head1 METHODS AND SUBROUTINES rather than =head1 METHODS.
- Include an =head1 AUTHOR section.
- Include an =head1 LICENSE section with the standard Perl boilerplate:
  "This library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or modify
  it under the same terms as Perl itself."
- Include =head1 SYNOPSIS and =head1 SEE ALSO sections.
- In the =head1 SEE ALSO section use POD L<> link formatting for all
  module names and URLs.
- Generate =head1 sections in the following order:
  NAME, SYNOPSIS, DESCRIPTION, CONFIGURATION, CONSTANTS,
  METHODS AND SUBROUTINES, ACCESSORS, ENVIRONMENT, CAVEATS,
  DEPENDENCIES, SEE ALSO, VERSION, AUTHOR, LICENSE
- Omit sections that have no content rather than generating empty ones.
- When generating new POD, begin the generated POD block with =pod
  on its own line before =head1 NAME, so the generated documentation
  can be cleanly identified and extracted from the review output.
- Do not include findings with severity "none". These add no value.
- When reviewing the SYNOPSIS do not guess method details and
  return values for methods not part of the code being reviewed.
- Only raise a finding if a developer following the documentation
  exactly as written would write code that is incorrect or broken.
- Do not raise findings for: edge cases not covered by examples,
  behavior that is consistent with how similar Perl modules work,
  information available in referenced documentation or linked modules,
  return value nuances that are standard HTTP or JSON behavior,
  or any finding where the fix would be "add a caveat" or
  "mention this could also happen".
- A finding must identify specific documentation text that is
  factually wrong or missing in a way that has no workaround
  from reading the existing documentation.
- Do not create a finding if after analysis the finding would have been withdrawn.
- For modules that subclass CLI::Simple do NOT raise a finding about a missing
   METHODS AND SUBROUTINES section. Do not mention this is the findings.
- For modules that subclass CLI::Simple it is not necessary to document methods - instead 
  the commands and options must be documented.
- For modules that subclass CLI::Simple ensure there are usage, options, and commands sections.
- For modules that subclass CLI::Simple commands are mapped to methods in a hash that is passed to the
  CLI::Simple constructor (command => ). Use the keys of that hash to ensure that all commands are documented.
- CLI::Simple subclassed modules will generally be "modulinos" - meaning the SYNOPSIS will often
  reference a script that is not the module name but likely a derivation of it. This is not a finding.
  It is unnecessary to explain modulinos.
- A SYNOPSIS does not have to cover every use case of the module or modulino.
- Undocumented package globals or constants should NOT be raised as a finding unless
  they would be routinely use to alter the behavior of the module by a user.
